Some document settings are read-only, because they can only be set when you first create a drawing, or they are controlled by a standard.
View or change document settings related to standards, units, text, dimensions, and line widths for the current drawing.
You can create as many title blocks as you need and switch between them. You can also toggle the border and title block on or off independently.
Change the sheet size and title block for the current drawing.
Creates a DXF file of the current drawing.
Creates a drawing template of the current drawing configuration that can be used when creating new drawings.
A template retains the current drawing's drafting standard, annotation and sheet settings, title block, and border. All drawing views, associated annotations, and parts lists are removed.
Add a new sheet which by default inherits the properties of the active sheet, or select the desired options.
Right-click anywhere within the sheet bar to add a new sheet there.
Select existing balloons to align, then specify two points.
Balloons are aligned and distributed equally between the two points.
Measures the precise distance between two points. Create dimensions that are parallel to the locations or objects that you specify.
Measures the angle of a rounded edge or the angle between two points or edges.
Specify the arc's start point, middle point and end point.
Creates a leader within the sketch.
Specify the leader's start point, then its end point.
Specify a point then enter the attribute's prompt. When finished, click outside the text editor.
Select a component within a drawing view, then place the balloon.
Specify a starting number, then select existing balloons or bend identifiers.
Balloons and bend identifiers are renumbered based on the order they are selected. Parts lists and bend tables will automatically sort based on the renumbering.
Select an existing linear dimension, then specify a point to create a new dimension.
Continue specifying points to create multiple dimensions all originating from the same base point.
Select a bend centerline within a flat pattern drawing view. A bend identifier is created.
Closes the editor and returns to the drawing or drawing template.
Inserts the selected image into the current block definition.
Select rounded edges, such as holes or fillets. A center mark pattern including a PCD is created.
Select an existing centermark pattern for editing.
A Reference Edge has to be selected while creating a center mark pattern for a slot.

Select the edges of features (e.g. holes) in the appropriate order to form the required center mark pattern. The Auto-complete checkbox is checked by default. The Center Mark Pattern is created automatically when you click just one hole or rounded edge.
Select two straight edges. The centerline is created between them.
Select a rounded edge, such as a fillet, hole, sphere, or cylinder.
Select an existing linear dimension, then specify a point to create a new dimension.
Continue specifying points to create multiple side-by-side dimensions.
Creates a circle using its center point and radius.
Specify the circle's center point, then specify a second point to define its radius.
Select objects to copy, specify a base point, then specify a second point to define the copy's location.
For more control over drawing defaults, make adjustments in Preferences in your User Name drop-down in the top right.
Standard and Units cannot be changed once a drawing is created. Sheet size, however, can be adjusted at any time in Sheet Settings.
Generates a parts list of the model associated to the drawing.
Select an edge, or an existing dimension, or an existing feature control frame symbol, then place the datum identifier.
To create a surface symbol in an ISO drawing, select an object, right-click to activate the marking menu, and select Surface.
Symbols can be added from the text field in the drop-down menu.
Select a rounded edge, such as a fillet, hole, sphere, or cylinder, then place the dimension.
Select existing dimensions or leaders, then add or remove breaks where they overlap other dimensions and leaders.
Dimension Break breaks the selected intersecting dimensions at the intersection points. You can also add a Dimension Break to other objects like Balloons, Bend Identifiers, and Leaders.
Right-click on selected dimesnions to create Dimension Breaks.
Select a dimension to modify its properties.
You can restore default properties if you modify the precision, alternate units, or tolerance type. Select the dimension, right-click to access the marking menu, and select Restore Defaults.
To change the settings for all dimensions on a sheet, use Annotation Settings at the bottom of the drawing area.
Select two straight edges. An edge extension is created for each edge that terminates at their intersection.

The first two points of the ellipse determine the location and length of the first axis. The third point determines the distance between the center of the ellipse and the end point of the second axis.
Select objects to delete, then press Enter.
Deselect objects by holding Shift while dragging across or clicking objects.

Click and drag to select multiple objects. A selection box from left to right will select all objects completely within the box. A selection box from right to left will select all objects partially within the box.
Hold either the Shift or Ctrl keys to select multiple sheets on the sheet bar to output a DXF
Creates a PDF file of the current drawing.
Creates a CSV file of the selected table
Hold either the Shift or Ctrl keys to select multiple sheets on the sheet bar to output a PDF. Check the Open PDF check box to open the PDF when the output is done.
Select the objects to extend. All objects automatically become extension boundaries.
Select either an edge or an existing dimension, then place the feature control frame.
To create a surface symbol in an ISO drawing, select an object, right-click to activate the marking menu, and select Surface.
Symbols can be added from the text field in the drop-down menu.
Select a hatch to modify its properties.
Each hatch has its own properties. You can only modify one hatch pattern at a time.
Double-click a hatch to modify the hatch properties of a section view. Edit the hatch pattern, the scale factor, and the angle of the hatch pattern.
Edits the selected image into the current sheet.
Specify the arrowhead location, specify the location of the text, then enter text. When finished, click outside the text editor.
You can control the font style and text height for all annotations in the drawing by clicking Annotation Settings at the bottom of the drawing area.
You can include special characters and symbols by entering a control code or a Unicode string.
Specify the line's start point, then specify a second point to define its angle and length.
Measures the horizontal or vertical distance between two points. Create dimensions by selecting an edge or by selecting two points.
Specify the arrowhead location, specify the location of the text, then enter text. When finished, click outside the text editor.
You can control the font style and text height for all annotations in the drawing by clicking Annotation Tools at the bottom of the drawing area.
You can include special characters and symbols by entering a control code or a Unicode string.

Reports distance, angle and positional data for the selected points.
Select objects to move, then click Transform. Then specify a base point and a second point.
Deselect objects by holding Shift while dragging across or clicking objects.

Click and drag to select multiple objects. A selection box from left to right will select all objects completely within the box. A selection box from right to left will select all objects partially within the box.
Generates a parts list for single component, assembly and animation references, and bend tables for sheet metal flat patterns references.
To change the part number and description of a component, modify the component's properties in the Model workspace.
A parts list that is placed in the bottom half of the drawing sheet will flip its numbering, so that the parts are numbered from bottom to top. To lock or unlock flipping, press Shift.
Select the object to offset, enter the offset distance, then specify a point to define to side.
Define view origins and place ordinate dimensions referencing them.
To change the part number and description of a component, modify the component's properties in the Model workspace.
A parts list that is placed in the bottom half of the drawing sheet will flip its numbering, so that the parts are numbered from bottom to top. To lock or unlock flipping, press Shift.
Select a rounded edge, such as a fillet, hole, sphere, or cylinder, then place the dimension.
Creates a rectangle using 2 diagonal points.
Specify the rectangle's start point, then specify a second point to define its width and height.
Select objects to rotate, then click Transform. Then specify a base point and a rotation angle.
If you want to redefine your selected objects or re-specify the base point without canceling the command, click Selection to return to Selection mode.
After specifying a base point, click Reference Selection to define a reference angle along an edge or between any two points.
Creates linear, aligned, angular, radius, and diameter dimensions.
Select objects, points, edges, existing dimensions, or select two points. Then place the dimension. The most appropriate dimension type is created.
Enters Sketch mode and creates a new sketch on the current sheet.
Select Finish Sketch to exit out of the mode.
Select an edge, or an existing dimension, or an existing feature control frame symbol, then place the surface texture.
To attach a surface texture to a surface in an ISO drawing, select an object, right-click to activate the marking menu, and select Surface.
The available properties in the dialog box depend on which symbol type is selected, and the drafting standard in use.
Insert a blank table to add data manually.

To change the width of a column without changing the width of other columns, select a cell and use the grips that appear around that particular cell. The overall width of the table changes but the other columns maintain the same width. To change the width of a column without changing the overall width of the table, select the whole table by clicking on table or cell border and use the grips that appear on table columns.
When a cell is selected, double-click to edit the cell text. You can also start entering text when a cell is highlighted to replace its current content.
Inserts the selected image into the current sheet.
When you insert your own title block, the origin point (0,0) in the DWG will equate to the bottom right corner of the Fusion Drawing border.
The drawing's standard, ASME or ISO, defines the default title block. You can insert your own DWG file as a title block using Insert Title Block within Sheet Settings.
Select the objects to trim. All objects automatically become cutting boundaries.
Generates a base view of the referenced design.
When the drawing template is used to create a new drawing, the placeholder is updated to show the referenced design.
Base view orientation can only be set during creation, while other attributes can be modified afterwards. Make sure the view orientation is how you'd like it before clicking OK.
Generates a drawing view that is derived from your selected 3D model. You can use a base view as a parent for other views.
Shows a specific portion of a view at an enlarged scale.
Select a parent view, specify the center point, specify the detail boundary, then place the detail view.
If you select the detail view boundary, you can use the gray grips to reposition the boundary. The detail view automatically updates.
Specify the center point of the area to magnify, specify the size of the boundary, then click to place the detail view. Modify the scale and edge visibility properties and click OK when done.
Select a view to modify its properties.
Projected views, detail views, and section views inherit properties from their parent view. If the properties of a view change, it will no longer inherit the settings from its parent view.

When moving a projected view, you can press Shift to break that view's alignment with its parent. For example, if a projected view's alignment is “locked” vertically or horizontally with a base view, you can click Move on the toolbar, select the view, then press Shift to “unlock” the alignment. Press Shift again to realign the view.
Generates projected orthogonal and isometric views.
Select a parent view, click to place projected views, then press Enter. The position of the cursor determines the type of projected view you create.
Generates projected and isometric view placeholders.
When the drawing template is used to create a new drawing, the placeholders are updated to show the referenced design.
Generates a full, half, offset, or aligned section view.
Use a section line to cut through a drawing view in order to reveal what is inside.
To modify a section view, click an existing section line and adjust the gray grips. If the path of the section line changes, the section view automatically updates.
Click to specify the path of the section line. When complete, press Enter to generate the section view, then click to place it.
Generates a simple (single segment cutting plane) section view from a drawing view.
Select a parent view, then specify the section line's start and end points, and then specify the insertion point for your section view.
Creates a sheet for each linked component in the design
For more control over drawing defaults, make adjustments in Preferences in your User Name drop-down in the top right.
Standard and Units cannot be changed once a drawing is created. Sheet size, however, can be adjusted at any time in Sheet Settings.
After you select a source and click OK, the Title Block contextual environment opens, where you can create and modify geometry and text to customize the title block.
Create a new title block based on an existing title block, from scratch, or from a DWG file.
This sheet is out of date.

The selected template's configuration does not match the current drawing's configuration. Select a template using the same standard and units.
